  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Defining the React App**\n\nI\'m now clarifying the initial goal: to develop a React/TypeScript application for \"Stomach Oriental\", using the design specifications from the images and YAML/HTML. This app will need to accurately reflect the restaurant\'s authentic Chinese theme, as the design system dictates.\n\n\n**Synthesizing the Design**\n\nI\'m now integrating the design elements. The dark, high-contrast theme is key, with the bold \"Chili Red\" accents. I\'m focusing on the typography - *Syne*, *Plus Jakarta Sans*, and *Space Grotesk*. The layout calls for a 1200px max container with ample padding, and a combination of brutalist and cinematic styling that I\'m synthesizing. I need to implement thick lines, and subtle rounding. Red glows and glass-morphism effects are also critical, informed from the two HTML examples provided.\n\n\n**Refining the Structure**\n\nI\'m now focusing on the structure, blending the HTML examples. I\'ll use the second HTML\'s polished, modern approach as a base, especially for the hero and glass card elements. I\'m prioritizing bold typography and a cinematic feel, informed by the YAML. Key sections include a hero, a menu with signature dishes, an about/story section, a location section, a footer, and the navigation bar.\n\n\n**Outlining the Component Architecture**\n\nI\'m now detailing the component structure. I\'ll use modular components in `src/components/`, with files for the navbar, hero, menu, story, location, and footer. These will be stitched together in `src/App.tsx`. I\'ll define types, if needed, in `src/types.ts`. I will use `lucide-react` for icons, which is preferred as it\'s cleaner than the HTML\'s suggested material symbols and is already included.\n\n\n\n**Constructing UI Elements**\n\nI\'m now detailing component styling. I\'ll need `.glass-card` and `.red-glow` custom classes. Dark mode will be forced via `body` styles. I\'m focusing on UI elements, starting with the navbar: it\'ll be fixed to the top with a logo, links for Menu, Legacy, and Location, and a \"Reserve\" call to action. I\'m focusing on the hero component, as well.\n\n\n**Planning the Sections**\n\nI\'m now detailing the planned sections. The Story and Location components will use a split layout with text on the left and an image on the right. In the Story, a large, faded \"STOMACH\" text will appear in the background. I\'m focusing on defining the Tailwind rules, which will allow us to define responsiveness.\n\n\n**Implementing the Styling**\n\nI\'m now integrating the font imports and Tailwind setup, incorporating the `@theme` block for color and font variables. I\'m translating the YAML variables into the Tailwind 4 format, and defining the glass-card and red-glow custom classes for styling.\n\n\n**Refining the Styles**\n\nI\'m now focusing on integrating custom styles. I\'ve defined `.hero-gradient` and `.red-glow` classes, and applied these to their appropriate elements. I\'m prioritizing the basic layout with a dark mode wrapper and customizing the body styling to use variables for background and text color, along with font families. I will also incorporate a more sensible icon strategy to keep things cleaner. I am using `lucide-react`, and mapping the HTML suggested icons to this library.\n\n\n**Mapping Icons**\n\nI\'m translating the icon suggestions to `lucide-react`. `social_leaderboard` will become `BarChart2`, or standard social icons if specified. `camera_indoor` maps cleanly to `Camera`. I am also now visualizing the primary components. I can see a glass-style navbar, a gradient-text hero, and the menu populated with the images.\n\n\n**Organizing the Components**\n\nI\'m now determining component file structure for better organization. I\'ll create `Location.tsx` and `Footer.tsx` within `src/components/`, while `App.tsx` will be edited to use the new components. To prevent a large, single file, individual files are safer and I will not group components.\n\nI\'m now integrating the font imports and Tailwind setup, incorporating the `@theme` block for color and font variables. I\'m translating the YAML variables into the Tailwind 4 format, and defining the glass-card and red-glow custom classes for styling.\n\nI\'m now focusing on integrating custom styles. I\'ve defined `.hero-gradient` and `.red-glow` classes, and applied these to their appropriate elements. I\'m prioritizing the basic layout with a dark mode wrapper and customizing the body styling to use variables for background and text color, along with font families. I will also incorporate a more sensible icon strategy to keep things cleaner. I am using `lucide-react`, and mapping the HTML suggested icons to this library.\n\nI\'m translating the icon suggestions to `lucide-react`. `social_leaderboard` will become `BarChart2`, or standard social icons if specified. `camera_indoor` maps cleanly to `Camera`. I am also now visualizing the primary components. I can see a glass-style navbar, a gradient-text hero, and the menu populated with the images.\n\n\n**Defining the Tailwind Styles**\n\nI\'m now integrating those CSS variables into Tailwind\'s configuration, mapping the custom properties for fonts, spacing, and utility classes directly. I\'m focusing on defining the glass-card, hero-gradient, and red-glow utilities, as well as applying them to the appropriate elements.\n\n\n**Implementing Scroll Functionality**\n\nI\'m now integrating scroll functionality to adjust background opacity. I\'ll utilize images provided in the HTML for the Hero section, specifically the second image. I\'m also incorporating the logo image from the provided source. I\'m focusing on these visual components as a start, to move toward functional scrolling.\n\n\n**Populating the Menu**\n\nI\'m now integrating menu items. I\'ve populated menu components with three image URLs and descriptions. I\'ll need to develop the layout for the menu itself, including image display and item details.\n\n\n**Refining the Implementation**\n\nI\'m now detailing standard React components with Tailwind classes. My focus is on minimizing tool calls to avoid errors. I\'ll consolidate actions with one `index.css` edit and a separate `App.tsx` edit.\n\n\n**Structuring the Components**\n\nI\'m now determining the optimal component structure, and have decided against combining section components, instead preferring individual files for each element within `src/components/`, such as `Navbar.tsx`, and `Hero.tsx`. I think this will lead to a simpler structure than a single \"Sections\" file. I\'ll need to create several files to contain each primary component.\n\n\n**Integrating the Theme**\n\nI\'m now integrating the provided CSS variables for fonts and colors into the project. I\'m focusing on defining a consistent theme via a stylesheet, along with implementing a Tailwind configuration that uses the defined variables. I am mapping the custom CSS variables for fonts, spacing, and utility classes, as well as applying the theme. I have defined `glass-card`, `hero-gradient`, and `red-glow` utilities.\n\nI\'m now integrating those CSS variables into Tailwind\'s configuration, mapping the custom properties for fonts, spacing, and utility classes directly. I\'m focusing on defining the glass-card, hero-gradient, and red-glow utilities, as well as applying them to the appropriate elements.\n\n\n**Refining the Theme**\n\nI\'m now streamlining the integration. I\'ve realized Tailwind v4\'s `@theme` automatically generates utility classes from CSS variables like `--color-*` for `bg-*` and `text-*`, and `--font-*` for `font-*`. I no longer need to define classes like `.font-headline`. I will adjust the theme implementation.\n\nI\'m now integrating those CSS variables into Tailwind\'s configuration, mapping the custom properties for fonts, spacing, and utility classes directly. I\'m focusing on defining the glass-card, hero-gradient, and red-glow utilities, as well as applying them to the appropriate elements.\n\nI\'m now integrating menu items. I\'ve populated menu components with three image URLs and descriptions. I\'ll need to develop the layout for the menu itself, including image display and item details.\n\nI\'m now determining component file structure for better organization. I\'ll create `Location.tsx` and `Footer.tsx` within `src/components/`, while `App.tsx` will be edited to use the new components. To prevent a large, single file, individual files are safer and I will not group components.\n\nI\'m now integrating the font imports and Tailwind setup, incorporating the `@theme` block for color and font variables. I\'m translating the YAML variables into the Tailwind 4 format, and defining the glass-card and red-glow custom classes for styling.\n\nI\'m now focusing on integrating custom styles. I\'ve defined `.hero-gradient` and `.red-glow` classes, and applied these to their appropriate elements. I\'m prioritizing the basic layout with a dark mode wrapper and customizing the body styling to use variables for background and text color, along with font families. I will also incorporate a more sensible icon strategy to keep things cleaner. I am using `lucide-react`, and mapping the HTML suggested icons to this library.\n\nI\'m translating the icon suggestions to `lucide-react`. `social_leaderboard` will become `BarChart2`, or standard social icons if specified. `camera_indoor` maps cleanly to `Camera`. I am also now visualizing the primary components. I can see a glass-style navbar, a gradient-text hero, and the menu populated with the images.\n\nI\'m now determining the optimal component structure, and have decided against combining section components, instead preferring individual files for each element within `src/components/`, such as `Navbar.tsx`, and `Hero.tsx`. I think this will lead to a simpler structure than a single \"Sections\" file. I\'ll need to create several files to contain each primary component.\n\n\n**Streamlining the Navbar**\n\nI\'m now implementing the `Navbar` component, adding scroll behavior for background changes. I\'m focusing on the fixed position, with a backdrop blur on scroll and applying the styles. I\'m currently using a conditional `className` to change the backdrop. I\'m focusing on integrating this into the design.\n\n\n**Implementing the Scrolling**\n\nI\'m now integrating the scroll-based background blur into the `Navbar`, using conditional classnames to adjust the backdrop. I am trying to refine the scroll integration to achieve a smooth visual effect that matches the design. I\'ve begun to integrate the navbar example, as well.\n\n\n**Refining the Hero Section**\n\nI\'m now implementing the Hero section and experimenting with visual effects. I will use the gradient text for the headline. I\'m focusing on the overlay, which calls for dark, cinematic styling, and plan to integrate a background image from the examples. I will adjust the opacity and blur.\n\n```text\nI\'m implementing the Hero section, integrating a gradient text overlay and a background image to enhance the dark, cinematic feel. I\'m focusing on adjusting the opacity and blur, aiming for an immersive visual experience for the user. I\'ve begun to integrate a new gradient.\n```\n\n\n**Consolidating Component Integration**\n\nI\'m now consolidating the component integration, and am moving towards combining sections within `src/components/Landing.tsx` as functional components. This approach aims to reduce file creation and potential errors by minimizing file edits. I\'m prioritizing keeping the directory structure clean, and the components localized.\n\n\n**Refactoring the Entry Point**\n\nI\'m now integrating `Landing.tsx` as the main section container, reducing complexity by consolidating sections within it and simplifying `App.tsx`\'s imports. I\'ll focus on reducing file edits and maintaining a clean directory structure, while prioritizing localization of components. Now, I\'m refactoring the CSS imports.\n\n```text\nI\'m implementing the Hero section, integrating a gradient text overlay and a background image to enhance the dark, cinematic feel. I\'m focusing on adjusting the opacity and blur, aiming for an immersive visual experience for the user. I\'ve begun to integrate a new gradient.\n```\n\n\n**Implementing the Theme**\n\nI\'m now integrating the theme definitions into Tailwind configuration, mapping CSS variables for color, fonts, and utilities to corresponding classes. I\'m focusing on creating glass-card, hero-gradient, and red-glow utilities.\n\n\n**Integrating Motion Effects**\n\nI\'m now integrating framer-motion into the project, as the design calls for cinematic elements. I\'ll use `<motion.div>` for smooth reveals on route transitions and other visual effects. I will utilize motion layouts to improve the cinematic styling.\n```\n\n\n**Finalizing the Implementation**\n\nI\'m now implementing Framer Motion for cinematic visual effects, and streamlining the component integration using `Landing.tsx` to combine the sections. I\'ve refactored the entry point and adjusted CSS imports. I\'ve confirmed image URLs for the logo and Hero BG. I can confirm this is a clean and robust approach.\n\n\n**Finalizing the Menu**\n\nI\'m now integrating the menu images and descriptions into the menu component, with links to full-size images. I\'ve populated the menu with all three images. I\'m focusing on the component layout and ensuring the menu is styled in the high-contrast design.\n\n\n**Defining the Section Order**\n\nI\'m now determining the section order. I will implement Hero, Menu, Story, and Location, in that order, followed by the Footer. I\'m focusing on defining the individual `src/components/` files and `src/types.ts` to implement data. I\'m integrating the required images for the Story and Location components.\n\n\n"
