  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Analyzing User Intent**\n\nI see the user is frustrated, which is important. They provided a general prompt for a \"cinematic movie/streaming hero section\" and clarified it\'s just a reference, allowing flexibility. My focus now is on what \"our needs\" means specifically, as that is the core of this conversation.\n\n\n**Refining Background Integration**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on integrating the cinematic style with the \"Stomach Oriental\" restaurant website. The user\'s goal is a landing page incorporating elements from the provided reference, specifically the full-screen video background, blur effects, and overlay. My current focus is how to use the provided video (`https://d8j0ntlcm91z4.cloudfront.net/user_38xzZboKViGWJOttwIXH07lWA1P/hf_20260406_094145_4a271a6c-3869-4f1c-8aa7-aeb0cb227994.mp4`) as an abstract background, or replacing it entirely with a sizzling food video. I\'m keeping the original video in mind, as the prompt specifies, \"BACKGROUND VIDEO\".\n\n\n**Prioritizing Video Content**\n\nI\'ve decided to prioritize the user-provided video as the background, as it\'s the more direct response to the prompt. My thoughts are progressing to the user\'s fonts; I will keep the restaurant\'s branding, with Syne for Headings, Plus Jakarta for body, Space Grotesk for labels. I will now integrate the liquid glass effect for the navbar and CTA buttons and apply `blurFadeUp` animation to the hero text. I also am structuring the landing page into a hero screen (full height, bottom content) and the rest of the restaurant landing.\n\n\n**Reconciling User Requirements**\n\nI\'m now reconciling the initial prompt with the user\'s actual needs, considering the full-height hero section versus a complete restaurant landing page. I realized the user wants a cinematic hero section *within* the context of the restaurant website, so I\'m now restoring the deleted sections (Menu, Story, Location, Footer) from my previous code, either by reconstructing or re-generating them.\n\n\n**Integrating Content & Design**\n\nI\'m now integrating the user\'s content and design preferences. I will use a video (or an image with a matching overlay) for the background, with a bottom blur overlay, plus liquid glass buttons. My focus is the hero text at the bottom, with copy like \"AN ALCHEMY OF ANCIENT FLAVORS\", supporting metadata and buttons. I\'m reconstructing the Menu, Story, and Location sections with their original content, and making sure the mobile menu is functional.\n\n\n**Implementing Navbar Integration**\n\nI\'m now implementing the Stomach Oriental logo and the specified navbar links: \"The Cravings,\" \"Our Legacy,\" and \"Find Us.\" I\'m ensuring these are properly linked to their corresponding sections on the page. The navbar will retain the existing slick animations. The hero section now fills the screen to its minimum height. Also, I\'m verifying that the `index.css` file contains both the restaurant theme variables and the cinematic utilities.\n\n\n**Evaluating Background Strategy**\n\nI\'m now contemplating background approaches. I\'m torn between a full video background or a solid background for the content sections. To avoid visual clutter, I\'ll use `fixed inset-0 z-0` for the video but apply `bg-surface` to lower sections. I\'ll also retrieve the first `Landing.tsx` structure to merge it with the cinematic design. I recall this was the component created in my first turn. I need to make a blend of my first and second turns.\n\n\n**Refining Color & Fonts**\n\nI\'m now integrating the user\'s provided CSS variables, specifically for color and font styles. I\'m focusing on incorporating the `--color-surface`, `--color-primary`, and `--font-headline` values. I am updating my existing theme to reflect these branding choices. I am now incorporating Tailwind CSS for utility classes.\n\n\n**Implementing Liquid Glass**\n\nI am now implementing the liquid glass effect specified in the prompt. I\'ve defined new Tailwind utilities for `liquid-glass`, `letter-wide`, `letter-tight`, and `hero-gradient`. I have focused on the hero text at the bottom, and buttons. I am also adjusting the blur to refine the effect\'s appearance, as well as applying the `hero-gradient`.\n\n\n**Optimizing Blur Animation**\n\nI\'m now implementing the `blurFadeUp` animation, along with configuring scrollbar styles. I have applied these animations and styles throughout the designated components. The liquid glass effect is now refined, and I am experimenting with various blur levels to achieve the desired effect on the hero text and buttons.\n\n\n**Prioritizing Page Structure**\n\nI\'m now focusing on arranging content. I\'ll maintain the full-screen hero section. The text will be at the bottom, and the subsequent restaurant sections will follow. For readability, I\'ll ensure the sections below the hero have a solid background, like `#131313`. I\'ve added a z-index to sections to ensure they sit above any fixed video, and I\'ve switched to `absolute` positioning for the background video within the hero section.\n\n\n**Composing Code Integration**\n\nI am now carefully rewriting `Landing.tsx` to integrate the cinematic hero with the remaining restaurant sections. I am also updating the hero\'s metadata to include a rating, establishment year, and location. I am updating the hero title and description copy, along with the CTAs. I will make a `Reserve a Table` CTA, and an `Explore Menu` CTA, and consider navigation arrows. I will keep the existing section structure, the menu section, the story section, the location section and the footer section. I will also incorporate animations throughout, to make sure everything scrolls organically.\n\n\n**Refining Integration Flow**\n\nI\'m now rewriting `Landing.tsx` to seamlessly merge the restaurant sections with the cinematic hero. I will integrate a scroll-down arrow with the liquid glass style. I\'ve imported `motion`, `MapPin`, `Plus`, and other icons. I\'m focusing on solid backgrounds for the sections following the hero. I\'ll make the video `absolute` within the `h-screen` hero. I\'m applying a bottom blur overlay using a linear gradient to create a seamless transition to the background color, and a new gradient.\n\n\n**Re-evaluating Font & Style**\n\nI\'m now incorporating liquid glass into the restaurant\'s theme, and updating the font styles. The liquid-glass effect will be applied to the Navbar and Action buttons. I\'m also implementing the `animate-blur-fade-up` animation for Hero elements. Finally, the remaining landing page structure will incorporate scroll-reveal animations using `motion` components, just like the initial draft.\n\n\n\n**Integrating Theme Updates**\n\nI\'m now integrating the provided CSS variables for the theme. I have updated the color palette with `--color-primary`, `--color-primary-container`, `--color-on-primary-container`, `--color-background`, `--color-on-background`, and `--color-on-surface-variant`. Also, I\'ve implemented the specified fonts: \"Syne\" for the headline, \"Plus Jakarta Sans\" for the body, and \"Space Grotesk\" for labels. The liquid glass utilities are also in effect now.\n\n\n\n**Implementing Liquid Glass Effects**\n\nI\'m now focusing on implementing the liquid glass effect, referencing the provided CSS. I will carefully translate these styles to the relevant components, particularly the navbar and buttons. I also am implementing the `blurFadeUp` animation. I am refining how the blur is displayed, with the aim to create the correct visual balance on the user interface, incorporating both transparency and subtle shifts in lighting.\n\n\n\n**Finalizing Landing Page**\n\nI\'m now writing and finalizing the `Landing.tsx` code. I\'ll replace the existing file content to ensure consistency. The goal is a full-screen hero section integrated with restaurant sections. The blur and `animate-blur-fade-up` effect will be in place with a transparent background, following the user\'s instructions.\n\n\n**Finalizing Animations & Nav**\n\nI\'m now integrating scroll animations with a focus on enhancing the mobile navigation and finalizing transition effects. I\'m leveraging `useEffect` to manage scroll states and modifying `Navbar` transitions based on scroll position, ensuring a clean and responsive mobile menu. I\'m also implementing scroll-triggered animations to improve the user experience as sections transition.\n\n\n**Refining Hero Content**\n\nI am now focusing on refining the hero section content, including logo, text, and navigation. I\'m applying the `blurFadeUp` animation to all elements, and I\'m ensuring the correct text display and logo integration. The navbar\'s transitions are being managed based on scroll position to improve user experience.\n\n\n**Finalizing NavBar Navigation**\n\nI\'m now writing the mobile navigation menu within the `Landing.tsx` code. I\'ll leverage the `useEffect` hook to manage scroll states for a smooth mobile experience. The navbar transitions will now be responsive to scroll position, to create a streamlined interaction, and I\'m ensuring all the `blurFadeUp` animations look correct.\n\n\n**Finalizing Visual Integration**\n\nI\'m now integrating the provided code, prioritizing seamless integration of the hero section with mobile navigation. I\'m focusing on responsiveness, ensuring all animations and effects are smooth and the mobile menu is intuitive. I\'m carefully reviewing the hero content display and ensuring proper scroll-triggered transitions, so that the user interface feels polished.\n\n\n**Composing Restaurant Sections**\n\nI\'m now carefully reconstructing and writing the restaurant section components (Menu, Story, Location) to match the provided structure. I am placing these components after the hero section, to maintain the desired flow of the user interface. I\'m focusing on ensuring these sections are fully functional and properly styled, keeping them distinct but complementary to the cinematic hero.\n\n\n**Rebuilding Core Restaurant Sections**\n\nI\'m now reconstructing the restaurant\'s core sections: Menu, Story, and Location. I\'m focusing on their content and visual style, ensuring they\'re properly positioned after the cinematic hero, and I will maintain my prior styling choices. These sections are being crafted with a focus on distinct, yet integrated, design choices.\n\n\n"
