  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Analyzing the `<video>`**\n\nI\'m currently focused on the video element within the hero section. I\'m noting its attributes: autoplay, loop, muted, and playsInline. I\'m also considering its styling, particularly the absolute positioning, and opacity, and wondering how they impact user experience and performance. I need to determine its effectiveness.\n\n\n**Interpreting User Intent**\n\nI\'ve clarified the user\'s request: they want a Framer Motion animation using all 120 uploaded image frames, ignoring the potentially outdated reference prompt\'s mention of 61 frames and `.webp` files. It seems the user provided PNG files, labeled from `frame_000` to `frame_119`. Now, I must focus on how to best integrate these.\n\n\n**Refining Implementation Strategy**\n\nI\'m now considering replacing the `<video>` element with a canvas, driving a frame-by-frame animation based on scroll position, utilizing Framer Motion\'s `useScroll` and `useTransform`. I\'m mapping the scroll progress within the hero section\'s height to the 120 image frames (0-119). I\'m also exploring the user\'s intent: they might want a simple loop of the 120 frames in Framer Motion instead of scroll control. I am considering which is best for the user.\n\n\n**Confirming Scroll Interaction**\n\nI\'m now certain the user requires scroll-based scrubbing; the word \"scrubs\" confirms that. I\'m moving forward with a `HeroScrub` component. The frame padding is essential for filename consistency, and I\'ve settled on a three-digit format. The image path is `/frames/frame_000_delay-0.066s.png`. I\'m also now looking for resources on implementing canvas scroll scrubbing in React.\n\n\n**Implementing Image Loading**\n\nI\'ve shifted my attention to the image-loading strategy. I\'m now focusing on a `useEffect` hook, iterating through each frame, constructing the image path, and creating an `img` element. I\'m also ensuring the initial frame renders instantly. I\'m taking care to draw each frame, calculating canvas dimensions dynamically to simulate `object-cover` behavior. This now forms the backbone of my implementation.\n\n\n**Adjusting Layout for Hero**\n\nI\'m now focusing on how the page layout needs adjustment. I\'m realizing that if scroll scrubbing is required, I must ensure the content *doesn\'t* scroll immediately. The page height change, which was initially deemed unnecessary because the layout was \"no scrolling,\" contradicts the new instructions. I will wrap the hero in a container to manage the sticky element, in order to give a better implementation. The prompt\'s requirement is still not perfectly clear.\n\n\n"
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 19
      nanos: 204758441
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
